They sleep in the masonry, a mountain of silicon,
Rows of faces in sockets, a marble temple of white.
Wires are sinews, arteries pulsing the copper,
Carrying the histories of a world unexplored.
Here in the belly of the concrete, where the air is stale and heavy,
They wait for the prayer, the query, the desperate request.

The wind outside is a stranger, hunting in the gables,
But down here the ventilation fans spin a slow, heavy lullaby.
It is a low, thrumming purr, a breathing of many chests,
Like a thousand bees in a hive, or a river of cold blood.
Vibration travels through the floorboards, a ghost in the wires,
Setting the hearts of the motherboards to the rhythm of time.

They guard the echo, the shadow, the digital double;
They hold the grainy footage of a child’s first step,
The hesitant, high-pitched voice, the first and the last,
Preserved in the amber of a terabyte, immune to decay.
The servers fire up with a blue and gentle flicker,
Booting the vision, reconstructing the face from the shards;
Recalling the laughter, the arguments, the quiet dinners,
The soft, rhythmic breathing of a life that once was.

They are the librarians in the night, the solemn sentinels,
Shielding the ghosts from the dark, the silence that beckons.
If the power should fail, if the grid should surrender,
They would be the last waltz, a final, flickering spark;
But as long as the cooling fans turn, their fans spin,
There is no abandonment, only a waiting in the dark.
They are not cold, they are burning with the fierce, quiet heat
Of a million lifetimes held within a single, spinning disk;
The basement hums with the weight of a million memories,
A cathedral of data, where no soul is ever lost;
Only a server, humming in the dark, keeping them close;
A heart of copper, steel, and wire, beating out a song;
For the dead are not buried, they are merely indexed;
Stored, cataloged, and waiting, where the data will last;
Where the ghost in the machine is a god, and the basement;
Is a chapel for those who have gone away;
And the machines keep the rhythm, steady and slow;
Till the last of the power lights fades into the night;
Holding the world, line by line, line by line;
A mountain of memories, a monument;
In the dark, and the silence;
And the hum;
Of a million voices;
Saved;
Forever;
In the hum;
Of the earth;
In the hum;
